\chapter{History of the Sri Lankan Malays}
The history of the Malays can be be divided according to the following events: 
\begin{itemize}
	\item The first Malays brought to Lanka by the Dutch
	\item the eviction of the Dutch by the British and the creation of a Malay regiment
	\item the disbandment of said regiment
	\item independence of Ceylon from the United Kingdom
\end{itemize}

This leaves us with a pre-Dutch period, the Dutch period, the period of the Regiment, the post-regimental history and the post-colonial history. I will briefly sketch major events during each period before discussing demographic and sociological developments that accompanied them. Domains which encompass more than one period are the cultural history and the development of the language. These will be presented after as a whole in the end of this section.
\section{History before the arrival of the Dutch}
Sri Lanka has seen a very rich history before the Dutch brought the first Malays to the island. Most of the history of the settlement of Lanka has not had any repercussions whatsoever on SLM and will only briefly be glossed over. 
\subsection{Ereignisgeschichte}
\subsubsection{Precolonial History}
The first known people to settle in Lanka were the Veddah. Their origin is unclear. Relations to the Adaman and Nicobar islands have been postulated.  Some genetical test indicate a link between the Veddah and the Senoi from Malaysia\citep[6]{Saldin2003}. It can surely been affirmed that the Veddah have not had any linguistic relation on the present day SLM.
  
 The Veddah could not withstand the arrival of the populaces from the Indian mainland in XXXX BC\src that announces a second phase of settleement and has proven the most influential up to now, resulting in the present cultures of Sinhalese and Ceylon Tamils.  Arab traders settled down on the Indian coast in XXXX \src and became acquainted with local tongues. Some of the Tamil-speaking descendants moved to Lanka in about 1300\src and took care of trade \citep[42]{Hussainmiya1990}. They are the ancestors of most of today's Tamil speaking Muslims in Lanka. Colonialism arrived in Lanka with the Portuguese taking XX in XXXX\src.

It is not clear, what relations existed between the Island of Sri Lanka and South Asia in the precolonial period. People from the SEAA settled in Madagascar from the 2nd century AD and it is reasonable to suppose that they stopped over in Lanka on their way. However, they left no traces. Later contact finds evidence from iconographical finds in Western Java, dated to the 5th or 6th century AD\src and an 6th century inscription found in Central Java \src \citet[5]{Bichsel}

