\subsubsection{History during Portuguese rule}
In 15xx the Portuguese gained hold of some islands \src in the SEAA. By that time, Islam had made considerable inroads in SEAA.
In 1506, the Portuguese conquered large parts of Lanka. They stayed until they were evicted by the Dutch in 1640\src. The Portuguese wanted to spread Christian faith and kept other religion in very low regard, especially Islam. It seems implausible that the Portuguese brought Malays given their hatred for Islam.\citep[cf.][34f]{Hussainmiya1990}

\citet[6f.]{Bichsel} affirms that there is no historical evidence of a sizeable Malay community in Sri Lanka and doubts that the Portuguese, who persecuted Muslims, would have tolerated the spread of Malays in Sri Lanka. 

However \citep[26]{Powell1973} mentions that some \em Javas \em (Malays) and \em Kaffirs \em (Africans) fought for the Sinhalese king Raju in 1587 and states that they had deserted from the Portuguese. We must thus assume that at least some Malays had been brought to Lanka by the Portuguese
 \citet[5f]{Jayasuriya2001} affirms that there is evidence for contact between Sri Lanka Portuguese Creole and Malayan Dutch. He seems to imply that this must have taken place during the Portuguese period, but a later contact between SLPC speakers and Malay Dutch speakers is also conceivable.


