\subsection{Demographic history before arrival of the Dutch}
There was no important settlement of Malays in Lanka before the arrival of the Dutch. Chandrabh\=anu's invasion did not last long enough to give birth to a Malay community in Lanka. If any Malays were left behind after the invasion, they would have merged in their correligionist community of Sinhalese Buddhists.

\section{History during Dutch rule}
The Dutch ruled Lanka from 1640 -- 1796. The Malays that came during their reign form the origin of today's Malay population in Lanka.

\subsection{Ereignisgeschichte}
The Dutch evicted the Portuguese from Sri Lanka in 1640. During
that time, they were already controlling large parts of the SEAA and thus commanded companies of Malay soldiers. Having Malay troops in Lanka had several advantages for the Dutch: First, those were used to tropical climate and fights in the jungle\draftnote{src}, second, they were not likely to side with the Sinhalese or Tamils in any rebellion given the cultural and religious differences. 

