\subsubsection{Soldiers}
The group that consituted the most important Malay influx were the soldiers. Already during the battles against the Portuguese, Malay troops were present \citep[44]{Hussainmiya1990}. Later, they formed an important part of the Dutch millitary presence in Lanka. There were garrisons in the main coastal towns of Colombo, Galle, Chillaw and Trincomalee\draftnote{structure of the army? all same place or dispersed?}. Malays were not confined to the lower rank, there is mention of a Malay captain in \citep[48]{Hussainmiya1987}.
 
 A regular supply of new recruits from Batavia was provided each year, as well as reninforcements in urgent cases \citep[48]{Hussainmiya1987}. The importance of the Malays for the Dutch army can be seen from the fact that `` [a]bout two thirds of the fighting troops were Malays'' \citep[37]{Powell1973} in 1764. From 1785 on, local, i.e. Lankan Malays were recruited into the Dutch army instead of the Moors \citep[54]{Hussainmiya1987}.

