\subsubsection{exiles}
The exiles came from the Moluccas and the Lesser Sunda Islands. Later, there were also exiled Javanese princes. \citet[7]{Bichsel} also cites Bacan, Tidore, Timor, Madura and Sumatra. How much were there from each region, what language(s) might they have spoken, and how important were the exiles in the overall Malay population?

The Dutch called Malays first Oosterlingen and later Javaans. This might indicate a shift of proportions of population and goes well along with the Javanese succession wars in the late 17th century which brought more Javanese exiles to Lanka. Most of the exiles had their families with them at deportation time or they joined them later. We do not know how many exiles from each region were brought to Lanka\draftnote{do we really not?}. There should have been considerably less exiles than soldiers, though. Nobility is likely to speak a high or even literary variety of their vernacular language. In the Moluccas, this would have been AVBSVD, whereas in the Lesser Sunda islands, this would have beenn LISDJL. Javanese princes would have spoken a DFLSJF variety of Javanese.

