\subsubsection{soldiers}
The most important contingent of Malays brought by the Dutch were soldiers.  The soldiers were mainly recruited in Batavia. At that time, Batavia was a port city with many different peoples mingling.  There are records of the following ethnic groups serving in the military: Ambonese, Bandanese, Balinese, Buginese, Javanese, Madurese, Malays, which is almost all the major ethnic groups from the SEAA \kuckn.  In Lanka, they were referred to as \em  Javaans\em, but we see now that this is dramatically simplified. The ``Neo-Indonesians'' as \citep[57]{Hussainmiya1987} calls them were the base for the Malay society in Lanka. Already in Batavia, they are likely to have developped a group identity, which would have been strengthened  in the unknown foreign country.

In Batavia, there were different \em kampungs \em for the different nationalities( \citet[48,51f]{Hussainmiya1990},\citet[cf.][11]{Hussainmiya1987}). It is nevertheless likely that intergroup communication took place. This would have been in some kind of Vehicular Malay. The Dutch need for soldiers was so dramatic that the \em kampungs \em were virtually depopulated at times \citep[56]{Hussainmiya1987}.

Depending on the military needs of the Dutch, there were more or less Malays in Lanka. Under normal conditions, there were 800 men in service, divided into 10 companies.  In 1764 the number of Malays rose to 2500.

in 1795/6 there were probably around 1400 Malays serving, comprising recruited civilians. \citet[49f]]{Hussainmiya1990} estimates the number of Malays in SL at around 2400 in 1800, possibly their highest figure \citep[54]{Hussainmiya1987} because the Dutch were anticipating a British attack and had stocked up.

