\section{History during British rule}
\subsection{Ereignisgeschichte}
The British took over from the Dutch in 179x. The Malay soldiers defended fiercely and are even said to have been the only worthwhile enemy of the British \citep[cf.][42,44]{Powell1973}. This earned them the respect of the British. From the Malay prisoners of war first sent to Madras, the British recruited many to serve in their native army in Ceylon.


\subsubsection{Governor North}
The British regarded the Malays as an exclusive soldier class. Even the Malays that had been civilians recruited as a last resort by the Dutch were granted full soldier status\draftnote{src?}. The British had a native Regiment in Ceylon which bore several names during the history of its existence: Malay Corps, His Majesty's Malay Regiment, the First Regiment, and finally the Ceylon Rifle Regiment.\draftnote{plag} 
% Military service formed a very important part of the Malay society in the 19th century, and their history can only be understood in conjunction with the regiment. [Something with the invalids' company]
The British kept on depending on Malays for their supply of native soldiers, because the Sinhalese and Tamils proved no good soldiers. But their number could not meet the needs of the British. Recruitment from abroad was encouraged and companies [?] were formed in Hambantota and Tangalle \citep[64f]{Hussainmiya1990}. In 1800, recruitment from Penang was started. This was the first time, that Malays from the Peninsula came to Lanka. The Regiment was a means to keep contact  with the SEAA.

From 1802, retired Malays were sent to the South and given land to colonize, first Hambantota, later Kirinda and Palatupana.
%1802: retired Malays sent to Hambantota, Kirinda and Palatupana to exploit the salt pans

18xx[or 179x?]\kuckn: North forms Boys' Regiment and company of invalids. Thus, most of the able bodied Malays were recruited into the army, and there were not many civilian Malays left. The percentage of recruited Malays rose to 75\%\draftnote{src?}. The social life evolved around the Regiment. The exiled princes were not recruited but given an allowance because North estimated them important for the social cohesion of the Malay population for the spiritual and cultural leadership they provided\citep[79]{Hussainmiya1990}. When some princes were made to colonize the South, they accepted to work like commoners \citep[63f]{Hussainmiya1990}.
In 1803, there was a war between the British and the Kandyan king in the inland of the island. many Malays deserted during this war.
Following this war, the Regiment only numbered 600 men \citet[72]{Hussainmiya1990}. 
Governor North left the island in 1805 to be replaced with Governor Maitland.

 

