\subsubsection{Malays in Kandy}\label{sec:malayskandy}
During Dutch and British rule, some Malays had escaped the colonial forces and fled to the independent kingdom of Kandy in the central upcountry. The first Malay  reported to have done so was a royal exile who slipped into Kandy in 1742 \citep[69]{Hussainmiya1990}. In 1765/66 Baron van Eck left behind a large number of Malay soldiers when retreating to Colombo \citep[37f]{Powell1973}. There were also more deserted soldiers and runaway slaves serving the Kandyan king who were held in high esteem \citep[78]{Hussainmiya1990}.
Also the British lost many Malays to desertion in the Kandyan Wars \citet[67]{Hussainmiya1990}.

The Kandy Malays remained true to their military inclination also in Kandy and served as soldiers and guards. The Kandyan king Wickremasinghe was eager to assure their loyalty as they were providing his body guards. But Wickremasinghe lost his temper in the end of his reign \citep[71]{Hussainmiya1990} and the loyalty of the Malays was split in the 1815 war with the British \citep[83]{Hussainmiya1990}, which the Kandyans lost and thus set an end to an independent Sinhalese kingdom in Lanka.
 
