\subsubsection{Governor Brownrigg 1812-}
Like Governor North and unlike Governor Maitland, Governor Brownrigg held the Malays in high esteem. He assembled all Malays into one regiment in 1813 \citep[81]{Hussainmiya1990}. He counted on his Malay Regiment to win the war against the Kandyan king in 1815 and 1818, a hope which was fulfilled \citet[68,82]{Hussainmiya1990}. However, many Malays had been sent back to the SEAA by Governor Maitland. Thus, there were not enough Malays to be recruited. Brownrigg  decided to bring recruits from abroad and chose Java. He founded the Royal Military school where the Malays were taught their own tongue and religion \citep[96]{Hussainmiya1990}.

