\subsubsection{The Ceylon Rifle Regiment}
The Ceylon Rifle Regiment (CRR) was founded in 1827 . Despite the change of the name, the conditions of service remained pretty much the same. But soon after the formation of the CRR, there was a shortage in recruits from the local Malays \citep[83f]{Hussainmiya1990}. The Malays seem to have changed their attitude towards military career. A not negligeable aspect was the reduction of pay. Other reasons were the enlistment for life, which was not popular, and the service whith Sepoys and Kaffirs, two groups which the Malays held in low esteem. Furthermore, there were now many possibilities of employment in civilian professions due to the growing economy, such as government, police and plantations. So the military had no longer a monopoly on the Malay work force.  

Failing to attract local Malays, the British again tried to recruit from abroad and opened a recruiting station in Penang in 1833. This station proved successfull in the beginning, but this was not to last long. The recruiting station shifted to Singapore in 1840, was stopped in 1842, revived in 1845 and finally abandoned in 1848. The Malays recruited during this period are said to be of ``low quality'' compared to the native Malays and the recruits from Java in 1813 and 1816.

From 1847 to 1854, a Malay detachment is sent to serve in Hongkong. Service in Hongkong was not popular and casulaties were high \citep[99]{Hussainmiya1990}. The popularity of the CRR with the Malays fell further ``By the 1850s it became relatively difficult to find Malays willing to serve in the CRR.''\citep[88]{Hussainmiya1990}

In 1848, the Regiment was engaged against the rebellion. This was its last military action. The regiment continued to shrink. In 1849 the Regiment was short of 483 men. In 1851, 22 companies were reduced to 18 companies, in 1854 to 14, of which 11 were Malay. In 1865, the detachments in Hambantota, Badulla, Kurunegala and Jaffna were withdrawn \citep[101]{Hussainmiya1990}. The police department took over some of the duties from the CRR. From 1870 onwards, the Malay element was dominant in the police \citep[102f.]{Hussainmiya1990}.
 
 The costs for the Regiment were important, but it had not been in use for warfare during 25 years. So, the Regiment was disbanded in 1873 and the remaining 700 Malays were discharged. 300 joined the police
Few discharged soldiers went back to the SEAA. Even after the disbandment of the Regiment in 1873, most Malays stayed in Lanka \citep[96]{Hussainmiya1990}. 

