The influx of new Malay people was the more important as Governor Maitland had sent back a good deal of the royal exiles in 1808, thus leaving the Malays in Lanka without their ``cream''. This meant that the days of aristocratic influence were over. Some of the descendants intermarried with the local Malay population\draftnote{?`Does this imply that they did not intermarry before?} But the Malay regiment officers stepped in and saw to the cultural issues of the Lankan Malays. 
 
If, in order to have a good base for a comparison, we only consider the recruits, and not the wives and children, 647 recruits came from the SEAA and 698 from the Malay peninsula. This disregards the Malays brought from Cochin/India. We see that the amounts are about even. The peninsular recruits would have spoken some form of Malay at arrival \kuckn whereas the recruits from the SEAA would have spoken some form of SJKHDSFD\kuckn. The recruits from the peninsula are said to be of ``low quality'' \src. It is thus not very likely that they had high prestige and others would imitate their speech. As for absoulte numbers, they matched the newcomers from the SEAA, but were few against the already established Malays, who have their origins not on the peninula. An important influence of the peninsular variety of Malay is thus not to be expected.

There are some records of recruits from abroad having brought their wives and children. This was encouraged by the British \citet[12,52]{Hussainmiya1987}. It is thus to be estimated that the number of immigrants is much higher than the mere number of recruited soldiers. \draftnote{schtzen}

In 1847, some companies were sent to Hongkong. Service in Hongkong was not popular and casualties were high. [Are there linguistic consequences for that? \kuckn]

In 1850, only 10 companies of 100 men were left.

In order to make recruitment more popular, the rules of the regiment were changed and allowed henceforth retirement after 15 years of service. Few Malays made use of this and went back to Singapore or Penang. A serious impact on the Malay society in Lanka is not to be suspected.
Even after the disbandment of the Regiment in 1873, only about 80 Malays leave Ceylon for Singapore. No one is known to have left for another destination

