\subsubsection{general}
The Malay can be said to have developped a distinct identity in the beginning of the 19th century both different from Lankans and Indonesians \citet[11]{Hussainmiya1987}.
Governor North classified the Malays into 3 groups: princes, soldiers and robbers. The latter were soldiers that had deserted because of low pay. The other two groups seemed to be well integrated into society. They are respected for their zeal which surpasses the Sinhalas' and the Moors'.
The exiles formed an important part of the Malay society and they ``lent a certain amount of cohesion, reflected glory and guidance to its members''\citep[79]{Hussainmiya1990}, but a good part of them was sent back in 1808.
The military officers then assumed the role of community leaders. They were well respected in the Regiment, even among British officers, as well as in the community. Until about 1850 the Regiment formed a central part of the Malay society with everything revolving around it. Security, solidarity and understanding among the famlilies characterized the live in the cantonment. Intermarriage among the Regiment was frequent. The social status of a community member could be evaluated by the number of officers attending his wedding \draftnote{or rank or name}. The houses were built close to the military administration center, as was the mosque where worships were held in the Malay language. 

The Regiment was bound by strong kinship ties. 
Many Malay families depended on the regiment as their only source of income \citep[78]{Hussainmiya1990}. Many soldiers joined because of family tradition.
The Malays had a certain sentiment of superiority regarding the Sepoys and Kaffirs.\draftnote{and also the Sinhalese and Tamils??}. Retired soldiers were either given land in the south or cash money. Malays seem to have prefered cash unless the land was close to the cantonment (Kampung Pensen in Kandy). This indicates the close ties and the cohesiveness of the community.

While the Regiment provided cultural and religious support for the Malays, the actual living conditions of the soldiers seem  to have been pretty poor. We  only have good  knowledge about the sociological circumstances of the Malays living in Colombo and Kandy. But in the South, things seem to have been worse.

The attractiveness of the Regiment began to decline in the 1820s. After 1850, the number of free Malays (\em Orang Priman\em) went up. New domains of work were the police, the firemen, other security related jobs, plantations, departments and offices. Generally, little is known about the activities of those people.

The cultural leadership of the Regiment was challenged towards the end of the CRR (1873). In an argument about the position of the Imam in the Malay mosques, the soldiers could not impose their candidate, and a certain kind of schism occured with military Malays and civilians attending different services. 

During the time of the Regiment lived in some kind of more or less autark community in the garrisons and their isolation aided the preservation of their identity \citep[1]{Bichsel}.

