\section{Cultural History}
\subsection{Literature}
We do not know about cultural achievements of the Malays before the British period. If there was literary activity, it could not have been widespread and be confined to religious texts \citep[143]{Hussainmiya1990}. During the Regiment, there was literary production in Malay, newspapers as well as artistic work. Artisitic work comprised adaptions of traditional topoi as well as the creation of own poems.

Genres found in Malay literatures are: religious kitabs, books on magic, sorcery and divination, catechism and prayer, family trees and personal memoirs \citep[135]{Hussainmiya1990}. There is a penchant towards religious, particularly mystic literature made for specialists.
The genre of `Syair' enjoyed particular popularity \citep[140]{Hussainmiya1990}.
There was no history of the SEAA dynasties. This can be understood as a sign of the affirmation of own identity \citep[140]{Hussainmiya1990}.

Literature was written in Malay. No other SEA language is attested. Poets used the Jawi script, also called Gundul. This name has a Javanese etymology, which might indicate that the exiles had brought literature to Lanka.

The authors were mainly retired soldiers which can be inferred from the fact that most manuscripts were found in the possession of descendents of soldiers.

Malay literature is not only to be read but also to be recited. The Regiment provided a frame for this. With the disbandment of the Regiment, this kind of literary (inter)action became much  more difficult. The poets moved away in search of work and it was difficult to have them meet.

There was exchange of books between Lanka and the SEAA, including grammars and dictionaries.

Literary interest was fostered by the British by the creation of a library-like recreation room for Malay officers \citep[146]{Hussainmiya1990}.

Literary activity stops in the beginning of the 20th century. This is because the last officers educted in the regimental schools died out, and the younger members of the community did not know how to write Malay. In their new civil occupation, knowledge of English and Sinhala or Tamil was more important.

Literary activity seems to have been confined to Colombo and Kandy.  \em Kampung Katukelle \em and \em Kampung Pensen \em are mentioned frequently as places of copying the manuscripts originated in Kandy.


Two newspapers were issued in Lanka, \em Alamat Langkapuri \em and  \em Wajah Selong\em. The former was popular with the established Malay population while the latter was preferred by the more recent arrivals \citep[156]{Hussainmiya1990}.

Cultural authority was exerced by priests and officers.\citep[138]{Hussainmiya1990}


The promoters of cultural acitivity in the Malay language were mainly retired soldiers. They kept up their literary interest after the disbandment of the Regiment, but when they eventually died, no one would replace them and the Malay literary tradition ikn Arab script died with them.

In 1906, the first literary work in Roman script is published \citep[149]{Hussainmiya1990}.

