\subsection{The question  of intermarriage}
Today, many Malays in Lanka count Sinhalese, Tamils or Moors among their forefathers. It is assumed throughout the literature that already in the early days, Malays intermarried, mainly with the Moors. According to \citet[19]{Hussainmiya1987} this has led to indistinctness of Malay and Lankan physical features. In the early days, there were not enough Malay women for all mercenaries, so the soldiers had to marry Lankan women. Their choice would then fall on Moor women because of the shared religion. The change towards Indian syntax that we observe in SLM would be brought about by those wives' incorrect acquisition of the language of the soldiers. It is assumed that the language change was very  We will return to the linguistic facts, motivations and sources of innovation later in this book.

The main authors on SLM are Anne Bichsel and Ian Smith. Both take their historic data from \draftnote{Vorname?} Hussainmiya and conclude that intermarriage between Malays and Tamils was frequent. This is also Hussainmiya's thesis. Let's take a look at the facts that Hussainmiya presents:

There is a citation from XYZ Schwitser \kuckn from 1xxx
\begin{quote}
	``The wives, which in part are Amboinese, in part Singulayans, and Malabarians''\citet[50]{Hussainmiya1987}
\end{quote}

Malabarians is an old term for Tamils. We see that there is indeed mention of intermarriage between Malays and Tamils, but the same is true for Singhalese. Some Malays had brought their wives from the SEAA.

\begin{quote}
	``Schwitser did not mention about the religious background of the Amboinese, and it may be that they were not followers of Islam, which explains partly why only Sinhalese and Malabar (Tamil) wives are mentioned in this case. Or it may be that the `Moorish' women were included in the racial terms of `Malabaris'.''\citep[68, foonote 68]{Hussainmiya1987}
\end{quote}

There are furthermore Dutch civil records, called \em tombos\em\footnote{Dutch has a dental stop in the beginning of this word which is associated with \graphem{th} in Lankan English. The correct spelling is nevertheless without \graphem{h}.} which point to marriages between Malays and Moors in the Dutch period. But if bride and groom are both Muslims, it is difficult to establish from historical records whether a given wife/husband was Malay or Moor given that both ethnic groups have a preference for Arabic names. Mohamed Rahaman can be Moor or Malay. Identification of Sinhalese and Hindu Tamils is somewhat easier are easy because a name like Sunil Jayawardhena  can only be born by a Sinhalese, and Murugan Adaikalanathan can only be Tamil. For intermarriage to be established, we have to have positive evidence that a Malay married a Moor. Some names are only born by Malays, such as Bangsajayah. But if Mr. Bangsajayah marries Fatima Hussein, we still do not know if this is a case of intermarriage. Fatima could be Malay or Moor. There are no names carried exclusively by Moors\kuckn.

Unfortunately, the exact \em tombos \em where Hussainmiya found his evidence are not revealed so that it is difficult to assess this question.

